Note 2 — The Kern Book Title
Throughout this article the 2000 Taschen publication is referred to as The Model Release. This title requires verification against the physical Taschen volume before the article is finalized. The argument built around the title — that Kern named the book after the legal document that encodes the split between the sisters, one of whom signed and one of whom did not — is structurally sound regardless of the exact title, because the model release as legal mechanism is independently verifiable from the Kern/McKenzie publishing record. However the specific claim that the title is The Model Release must be confirmed. This is flagged as an open verification item in the working evidentiary record.

Note 3 — Birth Years and the Public Record Discrepancy
The public institutional record — Wikipedia, MoMA, Tate, Buchholz, every auction catalog — records Lucy McKenzie as born 1977. This article asserts that 1977 is Kerri's birth year and that Lucy was born 1978, making the younger sister the one whose name carries the older sister's date of birth across every institutional register.
The evidentiary basis for this assertion is the Atelier E.B. Limited filing record at Companies House, company number SC487256, incorporated 22 September 2014. The filing history shows simultaneous appointment and termination of Lucy Mckenzie as director on the same date, filed as separate authenticated documents on 17 December 2014. The 36-page incorporation document filed on the same date contains the dates of birth that distinguish the two Lucy McKenzies in the register.
The incorporation document has not yet been pulled and examined for this article. The simultaneous appointment and termination is visible in the filing history screenshots and constitutes the primary public evidence of two distinct individuals operating under the same name in the same corporate record. Pulling the full 36-page incorporation document from Companies House directly is the verification step required to confirm the DOB distinction in the permanent record. This is flagged as the single most important open verification item.
The argument does not depend solely on the Atelier filing. The Wikipedia birth year of 1977 attached to an artist whose institutional career begins with work made in 1995 when she would have been seventeen or eighteen, whose Dundee enrollment runs 1995-1999, and whose Germany Erasmus year is 1997-98 — all of these are consistent with either birth year. The discrepancy becomes legible only when the Atelier filing is read alongside the two-sisters thesis. It is internally consistent with everything else in the evidentiary record and inconsistent with nothing. But it requires the incorporation document for confirmation.

Note 4 — The Kern/McKenzie Photographic Record
The distinction drawn in this article between the photographs in the Kern Taschen book — Kern's commercial work, circulated under the signed model release — and the photographs sold as art through the gallery system — likely Lucy's work, made in the same context from behind the camera — is an analytical inference from the structure of the collaboration rather than a claim based on a specific verifiable document.
The inference is supported by the following: Lucy McKenzie's early practice includes photography as a documented medium. The Kern collaboration runs 1997-99, the same period as her Dundee enrollment and Karlsruhe Erasmus year. Her subsequent gallery record includes photographic works from this period. The distinction between commercial photography owned by the photographer and fine art photography owned by the maker is standard in collaborative photographic practice. The model release governs the former. It says nothing about the latter.
The claim that Lucy was performing as Kerri in the Kern photographs — inhabiting her older sister's persona for the camera — is an interpretive argument supported by the overall two-sisters thesis and by the structural logic of the Kern project as described in this article. It is not independently verifiable from a single document. It is the interpretive framework within which the Kern/McKenzie record becomes coherent as a unified whole rather than a series of unrelated facts.

